47.title: Unforeseen Maximums are a resistant problem
47.text:
Summary:  Unforeseen maximums occur when a powerful cognitive process, given a fitness function F that you thought had a maximum somewhere around X, finds an even higher F-scoring solution X' that was outside the space of possible solutions you considered.  (Example:  A [programmer] considers possible ways of producing smiles by producing human happiness, and the highest-scoring smile-producing strategies in this part of the solution space look quite nice to them.  They give a neutral genie the instruction to produce smiles.  The neutral genie tiles its future light cone with tiny molecular smiley-faces.  This was not something the programmer had explicitly considered as a possible way of producing smiles.)

# Definition.

An unforeseen maximum of an [optimization process] is said to occur relative to some [programmer]'s expectations about that optimization process.  It generally implies that, on some stage of the optimization, most archetypally the utility function, there is a [fitness function] F for solutions.  The programmer thinks that F will have a maximum around a set of nice things X, with score roughly Y.  However, the optimization process is at least partially [advanced](AdvancedAgent), or possibly just cognitively different, and searches a solution space that includes possible high-scoring solutions that the programmer never considered.  The solution produced is outside X and scores Y' > Y under the stated fitness function F.

Unforeseen maximums are a problem if the general issue tends to pose a severe obstacle to the [safety](AdvancedSafety) of [advanced agents] with a directly coded or directly specified goal criterion.  They are a [patch-resistant problem] if simple attempts to avert an Unforeseen Maximum just cause a new Unforeseen Maximum somewhere else, and generally fail to make the actual maximum be the intuitively desired X.

## Example: Schmidhuber's compression goal.

Juergen Schmidhuber, during the 20XX Singularity Summit, gave a talk proposing that the best and most moral utility function for an AI was the gain in compression of sensory data over time. Schmidhuber gave examples of valuable behaviors he thought this would motivate, like doing science and understanding the universe, or the construction of art and highly aesthetic objects. [todo: someone needs to actually find the video and look up the year and find some direct Schmidhuber quotes.]

Yudkowsky in Q&A suggested that this utility function would instead motivate the construction of external objects that would internally generate random cryptographic secrets, encrypt highly regular streams of 1s and 0s, and then reveal the cryptographic secrets to the AI.

# Implications

UnforeseenMaximums are a major contributing factor to [formally coded object-level utility functions are unsafe] and [inductively learning the true value criterion will be difficult and dangerous].

2c.title: Advanced agent properties
2c.clickbait: How smart does a machine intelligence need to be, for its niceness to become an issue?  "Advanced" is a broad term to cover cognitive abilities such that we'd need to start considering AI alignment.

2pf.title: Low impact
2pf.clickbait: The open problem of having an AI carry out tasks in ways that cause minimum side effects and change as little of the rest of the universe as possible.

2qp.title: Conservative concept boundary
2qp.clickbait: Given N example burritos, draw a boundary around what is a 'burrito' that is relatively simple and allows as few positive instances as possible.  Helps make sure the next thing generated is a burrito.

2r8.title: Mild optimization
2r8.clickbait: An AGI which, if you ask it to paint one car pink, just paints one car pink and doesn't tile the universe with pink-painted cars, because it's not trying *that* hard to max out its car-painting score.

2sj.title: Safe training procedures for human-imitators
2sj.clickbait: How does one train a reinforcement learner to act like a human?

2v.title: AI alignment
2v.clickbait: The great civilizational problem of creating artificially intelligent computer systems such that running them is a good idea.

2w.title: Edge instantiation
2w.clickbait: When you ask the AI to make people happy, and it tiles the universe with the smallest objects that can be happy.

3d.title: Arbital
3d.clickbait: Arbital is the place for crowdsourced, intuitive math explanations.

3d9.title: 'Beneficial'
3d9.clickbait: Really actually good.  A metasyntactic variable to mean "favoring whatever the speaker wants ideally to accomplish", although different speakers have different morals and metaethics.

3hs.title: Author's guide to Arbital
3hs.clickbait: How to write intuitive, flexible content on Arbital.

3n.title: Arbital "parent" relationship
3n.clickbait: Parent-child relationship between pages implies a strong, inseparable connection.

41l.title: Superintelligent
41l.clickbait: A "superintelligence" is strongly superhuman (strictly higher-performing than any and all humans) on every cognitive problem.

43g.title: Missing the weird alternative
43g.clickbait: People might systematically overlook "make tiny molecular smileyfaces" as a way of "producing smiles", because our brains automatically search for high-utility-to-us ways of "producing smiles".

43h.title: Psychologizing
43h.clickbait: It's sometimes important to consider how other people might be led into error.  But psychoanalyzing them is also dangerous!  Arbital discussion norms say to explicitly note this as "psychologizing".

43w.title: Don't try to solve the entire alignment problem
43w.clickbait: New to AI alignment theory?  Want to work in this area?  Already been working in it for years?  Don't try to solve the entire alignment problem with your next good idea!

5f.title: Preference framework
5f.clickbait: What's the thing an agent uses to compare its preferences?

5l.title: Complexity of value
5l.clickbait: There's no simple way to describe the goals we want Artificial Intelligences to want.

5t.title: Object-level vs. indirect goals
5t.clickbait: Difference between "give Alice the apple" and "give Alice what she wants".

5v.title: Algorithmic complexity
5v.clickbait: When you compress the information, what you are left with determines the complexity.

6q.title: Context disaster
6q.clickbait: Some possible designs cause your AI to behave nicely while developing, and behave a lot less nicely when it's smarter.

6r.title: Methodology of foreseeable difficulties
6r.clickbait: Building a nice AI is likely to be hard enough, and contain enough gotchas that won't show up in the AI's early days, that we need to foresee problems coming in advance.

6w.title: Task-directed AGI
6w.clickbait: An advanced AI that's meant to pursue a series of limited-scope goals given it by the user.  In Bostrom's terminology, a Genie.

6y.title: Pivotal event
6y.clickbait: Which types of AIs, if they work, can do things that drastically change the nature of the further game?

9r.title: Programmer
9r.clickbait: Who is building these advanced agents?
